class="pw-post-body-paragraph nt nu gt nv b hr pu nx ny hu pv oa ob oc pw oe of og px oi oj ok py om on oo gm bj">First of all, we need to be able to get your current location, be it stationary or changing.</p><p id="30b5" class="pw-post-body-paragraph nt nu gt nv b hr nw nx ny hu nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol om on oo gm bj">Fortunately, this can be achieved via the <code class="cw pz qa qb qc b">geolocation.getCurrentPosition()</code> method which is a JavaScript inbuilt web API call that is used to get the current position of a device and representing that position in the form of latitude and longitude.</p><p id="4286" class="pw-post-body-paragraph nt nu gt nv b hr nw nx ny hu nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol om on oo gm bj">Implementing this method is quite easy, we simply use an <strong class="nv gu">IF/ELSE </strong>statement to get our current location:</p><figure class="nn no np nq nr nm"><div class="qd jv l fi"><div class="qe qf l"></div></div></figure><h1 id="2c25" class="oy oz gt be pa pb pc ht pd pe pf hw pg ph pi pj pk pl pm pn po pp pq pr ps pt bj"><strong class="al">Getting your current location‚Äôs weather data</strong></h1><p id="b4bc" class="pw-post-body-paragraph nt nu gt nv b hr pu nx ny hu pv oa ob oc pw oe of og px oi oj ok py om on oo gm bj">Now that we know where you are, the next step is to find out what the weather‚Äôs like.</p><p id="1dba" class="pw-post-body-paragraph nt nu gt nv b hr nw nx ny hu nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol om on oo gm bj">Lots of API providers were out there but we chose <a class="af oq" href="https://darksky.net/" rel="noopener ugc nofollow" target="_blank">DarkSky</a> to provide us with the data we need. To make an API call, we have to create a function <code class="cw pz qa qb qc b">showWeather</code> which will contain our URL. Our URL will have to contain the variables <code class="cw pz qa qb qc b">lat</code> and <code class="cw pz qa qb qc b">long</code> (both obviously will be arguments in <code class="cw pz qa qb qc b">showWeather</code>), these can be included with the aid of back-ticks (which are used to enclose template literals). To avoid problems created by Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS), we shall specify that our request format be in <code class="cw pz qa qb qc b">JSONP</code> , we shall also append a callback function <code class="cw pz qa qb qc b">displayWeather</code> that can be used to access the data retrieved from the API call.</p><figure class="nn no np nq nr nm"><div class="qd jv l fi"><div class="qe qf l"></div></div></figure><h1 id="df58" class="oy oz gt be pa pb pc ht pd pe pf hw pg ph pi pj pk pl pm pn po pp pq pr ps pt bj">Creating functions to modify the weather data</h1><p id="84a5" class="pw-post-body-paragraph nt nu gt nv b hr pu nx ny hu pv oa ob oc pw oe of og px oi oj ok py om on oo gm bj">More often than none, we‚Äôll have to modify the data we retrieved from DarkSky. Certain values might be different from what we actually want (temperature might be in Fahrenheit instead of Celsius, humidity could be in decimals and so on). To do this,<code class="cw pz qa qb qc b">Math.round()</code> is one of the methods we‚Äôll use extensively in our conversions.</p><figure class="nn no np nq nr nm"><div class="qd jv l fi"><div class="qe qf l"></div></div></figure><h1 id="6bc5" class="oy oz gt be pa pb pc ht pd pe pf hw pg ph pi pj pk pl pm pn po pp pq pr ps pt bj">Adding weather icons to our data</h1><p id="fa23" class="pw-post-body-paragraph nt nu gt nv b hr pu nx ny hu pv oa ob oc pw oe of og px oi oj ok py om on oo gm bj">Users want things easy. Asides seeing a summary about how it‚Äôs going to rain today, you want to also see dark clouds and thunderbolts as these are more likely to appeal to you than anything else.</p><p id="ceff" class="pw-post-body-paragraph nt nu gt nv b hr nw nx ny hu nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol om on oo gm bj">To achieve this, we had to attach weather icons (skycons if you will) to our weather data:</p><figure class="nn no np nq nr nm"><div class="qd jv l fi"><div class="qe qf l"></div></div></figure><h1 id="076e" class="oy oz gt be pa pb pc ht pd pe pf hw pg ph pi pj pk pl pm pn po pp pq pr ps pt bj">Displaying our weather data</h1><p id="5fae" class="pw-post-body-paragraph nt nu gt nv b hr pu nx ny hu pv oa ob oc pw oe of og px oi oj ok py om on oo gm bj">Now the grand finale, creating the interface for our app. Using HTML, CSS and JavaScript, this should be no trouble. We‚Äôll be sure to finish just in time to catch the Yankees game!</p><figure class="nn no np nq nr nm"><div class="qd jv l fi"><div class="qe qf l"></div></div></figure><figure class="nn no np nq nr nm or os paragraph-image"><div role="button" tabindex="0" class="ou ov fi ow bg ox"><div class="or os qg"><picture><source srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*ZrJKJqBsksWd-8uKM9OvgA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*ZrJKJqBsksWd-8uKM9OvgA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*ZrJKJqBsksWd-8uKM9OvgA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*ZrJKJqBsksWd-8uKM9OvgA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*ZrJKJqBsksWd-8uKM9OvgA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*ZrJKJqBsksWd-8uKM9OvgA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*ZrJKJqBsksWd-8uKM9OvgA.png 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" srcSet="https:/